# =============================================================================
# Local Development Environment Variables
# =============================================================================
# Copy this file to .dev.vars and fill in your values.
# This file is loaded automatically by `wrangler dev`.
#
# IMPORTANT: Never commit .dev.vars to version control!
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION A: Use Environment Variables (Recommended for security)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Set these to use hardcoded credentials. These take priority over KV storage.
# The Settings UI will show "Managed via environment variable" when these are set.

PRODUCTIVE_API_TOKEN=your_productive_api_token_here
APP_PIN=1234

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# OPTION B: Use Settings UI + KV Storage
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Comment out the variables above to use the web-based Settings UI instead.
# On first visit, you'll be prompted to enter your credentials via the setup page.
# Credentials are stored in Cloudflare KV (local SQLite during development).
#
# To use this option, comment out the lines above:
# # PRODUCTIVE_API_TOKEN=your_token_here
# # APP_PIN=1234

# =============================================================================
# Priority Order (when deployed)
# =============================================================================
# 1. Environment Variables (Cloudflare Secrets) - highest priority
# 2. KV Storage (from Settings UI) - used if env vars not set
# 3. Setup page - shown if neither is configured
#
# This means you can set env vars to "lock" credentials and prevent 
# users from changing them via the Settings UI.
# =============================================================================

# =============================================================================
# Getting Your API Token
# =============================================================================
# 1. Log into Productive.io
# 2. Go to Settings → API → Personal Access Tokens
# 3. Create a new token with read access
# 4. Copy the token value here
# =============================================================================
